As somebody who used to go without food for days when I was super depressed because the food I had that I could prepare easily wasn't apetizing at all, there is nothing more important than to figure out how to combine 'easy', 'nourishing', and 'tasty'

-How to make plant-based or ''''healthy'''' food taste good!!! 

Seriously, if you want people to eat more plant-based foods but you only tell them 'you have to or otherwise you're bad', how is that going to work???
@realest_ghost Why couldn't they just like, buy one pair of tofu sausages???
@realest_ghost Oh no, what the fuck :XXX

-How to do different kinds of exercises (so people could find something that they could have fun with)
-How to know when exercise is harming your body
-How to know when your eating behavior is not working for your mental or physical well-being

Things institutions could teach mentally ill people in regards to food and exercise that would not be super fatphobic and honestly, patronizing

-How to cook easy meals
-How to find recipes for easy meals
-How to buy fruits and vegetables for cheap
@realest_ghost Oh no

There was genuinely just zero interest in eating-related disorders in any of the screenings or therapies I was at, which baffles me

I'm still super grateful I got to go there bc talking with other people with mental health problems every day was incredibly helpful, but jesus

Also why is a healthy eating class ('Ernährungskunde', so 'Diet knowledge' basically) even a mandatory event at a psycho-social rehab??? How many people who take this class have eating disorders??? Likely not that few!!!
(Also, seriously??? Restricting herb water??? wtf???)
Telling Austrians they can't have as much chamomile tea as they can hold in their body is like telling Italians to stop eating tomatoes

The first one is something EVERYBODY IN AUSTRIA learns in first grade. With the exact same example.

The second one is fucking bonkers and also a cultural affront tbh

Maybe off-topic? I hope Cliff will forgiff

I am becoming a better person by reflecting on who I am. Which is hard and painful but if you give yourself some compassion, I really think it's one of the most important things you can do.

And one of the most important things I have to remind myself of: I am lucky enough to be in a creative position now. Which means that most of my work is _thinking_. Even writing this, which I am doing while NOT working, is relevant to my work.
And a lot of that is workplace trauma. But a lot of it is also low self-esteem, adhd, ocd and the scars my nearly healed depression left in me (catastrophizing is one of my favorite things)

But by just slowly adding clay to the sculpture of my project, just one little layer at a time, it gets. done. And still even though I know that I'm still so afraid that I can't do it every time. Every Single Time.

I never feel like I'm doing things 'well enough'. I don't know if I ever will. I need to cling to 'This just needs to get done, you just need to do this step, it doesn't have to be perfect, we can look through it again tomorrow', or I would never get anything done ever

But guess what happens then? I start reading, and then I start taking notes, and then slowly I build an outline for the text I have to write in my head, and once that outline is down, I will have that fucker written up in no time and the structure will be great

I still think about the project, I look at the materials (I don't read them most of the time, though, except maybe the most primary material), but I don't really work, bc I don't feel like I can at that point. And that is scary as fuck.

But the scary thing is that when I start a project, things go incredibly slow. I will plan the steps of the project, find the material I need, and then - often just don't do any relevant work for a day or two.

"I got this feedback for things I did my own way. When I did that work I was afraid that I wasn't doing enough, but look at this. I don't need to work like other people to do good work. It's ok if I don't work consistently. I still have great output. I'm still good at what I do."

It's honestly extremely scary because I have to actually _trust_ myself that I will do good work. I've started collecting any positive feedback I get into a folder on my desktop so I can actually look at these and be like
I just kinda feel it would be a good idea to share these things tbh
